{"id":1171,"parent_id":0,"book_id":8,"content_id":1,"language_id":1,"display_order":1171,"title":"Syria","subtitle":"","short_title":"Syria","uri":"/scriptures/bd/syria","content":[["div",{"id":"t1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/syria.t1","order":".000.3790"},[".title","Syria"],["div",{"id":"p1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/syria.p1","order":".000.3791"},"Originally known as Aram (or “the highlands”), a general name for the country north and northeast of Palestine. The people were of Semitic origin (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/gen/10.22"},"Gen. 10:22"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/gen/22.21"},"22:21"],") and were descended from the same stock as the Israelites. (See",["i",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/bd/aram"},"Aram"],"."],") At the beginning of the Hebrew monarchy Syria was divided into a number of small kingdoms, such as Damascus (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-sam/8.5-6"},"2 Sam. 8:5–6"],"), Maachah and Geshur (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-sam/15.8"},"2 Sam. 15:8"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/1-chr/19.6"},"1 Chr. 19:6"],"), Beth-Rehob (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-sam/10.6"},"2 Sam. 10:6"],"), and Zobah (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-sam/10.6,8"},"2 Sam. 10:6, 8"],"). These kingdoms were as a rule rivals of Israel (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-sam/8.3-6"},"2 Sam. 8:3–6"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/1-kgs/11.23-25"},"1 Kgs. 11:23–25"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/1-kgs/15.18"},"15:18"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/1-kgs/20.34"},"20:34"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/1-kgs/22"},"22"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/6.24?span=6.24-7.20"},"2 Kgs. 6:24–7:20"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/8.28-29"},"8:28–29"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/10.32-33"},"10:32–33"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/21.17-18"},"21:17–18"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/13.3-7,25"},"13:3–7, 25"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/14.28"},"14:28"],"). As the Assyrian kingdom grew stronger, Syria grew weaker, and Damascus was destroyed (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/16.7-9"},"2 Kgs. 16:7–9"],"). Under Seleucus Nicator (312",["span.small","B.C."],") Syria again became a powerful kingdom with Antioch as its capital. Antiochus the Great (223",["span.small","B.C."],") increased its strength, and Palestine became a Syrian province. Then followed the Maccabean rebellion (see",["i",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/bd/maccabees"},"Maccabees"]],"). In 66",["span.small","B.C."],"Syria was conquered by Pompey and became a Roman province; as such it is mentioned in the New Testament in",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/matt/4.24"},"Matt. 4:24"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/luke/2.2"},"Luke 2:2"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/acts/15.41"},"Acts 15:41"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/acts/18.18"},"18:18"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/acts/21.3"},"21:3"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/gal/1.21"},"Gal. 1:21"],"."]]],"refs":null}
